==Anglo-Saxon==

===Verb===
'''ǽtrian'''

# to poison, envenom ''transitive''
# to become poisonous ''intransitive''

===Pronunciation===
*ae:·tri·an, ye·ae:·tri·an; 

Note: this verb may appear with or without the [[ge-]] prefix, without a change in meaning

===Declension===
*Class 1a Weak Transitive Verb
====Present Tense====
=====Indicative=====
*Singular: ic ǽtrie, þu ǽtrest, hé ǽtreþ
*plural: wé, gé, híe ǽtriaþ
=====Subjunctive=====
*Singular: ǽtrie
*plural: ǽtrien
=====Imperative=====
*Singular: ǽtre!
*plural: ǽtriaþ!
=====Participle=====
*ǽtriende
====Past Tense====
=====Indicative=====
*Singular: ic ǽtrede, þu ǽtredest, hé ǽtrede
*plural: wé, gé, híe ǽtredon
=====Subjunctive=====
*Singular: ǽtrede
*plural: ǽtreden
=====Participle=====
*geǽtred
====Inflected Infinitive====
*tó ǽtrienne

===Etymology===
*Derived from [[ǽtrig]] ''poisonous'' and the verb suffix ''-ian''.  Ultimately derived from [[átor]] {{f}}, ''poison, venom; gall''.

===Derived terms===
*''Nouns'': [[ǽtrennes]] {{f}}
*''Adjectives'': [[ǽtren]], [[ǽtrenmód]], [[ǽtrig]], [[geǽtred]]

